And, finally, the ability to replace vectorization with explicit broadcasting using things like `sin.(x)` is a huge reduction in complexity.
Indexing into rows or columns of a matrix produces a vector now instead of the old divide where rows were matrices, but columns weren't.
In the past, I would never use untyped list comprehensions as they were just too brittle.
List comprehensions are safe to use now everywhere now because their behavior doesn't depend on type-inference.
You can use actual generator expressions like `f(i) for i in 1:n` now to produce iterables that don't expand into unnecessary dense arrays.
The old type distinction between ASCII and UTF-8 strings is gone, which made everything too complicated and little gain.
For me, that's just a huge documentation win as it makes the author's intent more clear to both the compiler and the human reader.
You can explicitly annotate the intended return type of a function, which will force outputs from that function to have that type.
This means you can get good performance while writing things like `map(x -> sin(x^2), randn(1000))` now.
Every function (even closures) has its own type now, so you can dispatch on functions and they're no longer blackboxes for type inference.

@egrefen @stanfordnlp That's correct: N layer LSTM + swapping = simple RNN in terms of memory; no swapping=more than 4*layers times as much
@egrefen @stanfordnlp No that was incorrect you need max memory of batch_size*hidden_size*timesteps*4, and this does not depend on the depth
@egrefen @stanfordnlp If you do this for every recurrent weight and weight, you have maximum memory of batch*hidden_size*timesteps*2.
@egrefen @stanfordnlp A swap costs about 35% of the time of the dot product, so you can swap both activities and errors at the same time.
@egrefen @stanfordnlp If you use pinned memory(!), you can swap errors/activities under the dot product of the previous errors/activities
